<h2 id="mp-tfa-h2" class="mp-h2 mw-html-heading">From today's featured article</h2>
<div id="mp-tfa" class="mp-contains-float"><div id="mp-tfa-img" style="float: left; margin: 0.5em 0.9em 0.4em 0em;">
<div class="thumbinner mp-thumb" style="background: transparent; color: inherit; border: none; padding: 0; max-width: 117px;">
<span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="Cover of first issue (October/November 1930)"><img alt="Cover of first issue (October/November 1930)" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg/120px-Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg" decoding="async" width="120" height="171" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg/250px-Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg 1.5x" data-file-width="1750" data-file-height="2500"></a></span><div class="thumbcaption" style="padding: 0.25em 0; word-wrap: break-word;">Cover of first issue (October/November 1930)</div></div>
</div>
<p><i><b><a href="/wiki/Oriental_Stories" title="Oriental Stories">Oriental Stories</a></b></i> was an American <a href="/wiki/Pulp_magazine" title="Pulp magazine">pulp magazine</a> published by Popular Fiction and edited by <a href="/wiki/Farnsworth_Wright" title="Farnsworth Wright">Farnsworth Wright</a>. It was launched in 1930 as a companion to Popular Fiction's <i><a href="/wiki/Weird_Tales" title="Weird Tales">Weird Tales</a></i>, and carried <a href="/wiki/Orientalism" title="Orientalism">stories with Far Eastern settings</a>, including some fantasy. Contributors included <a href="/wiki/Robert_E._Howard" title="Robert E. Howard">Robert E. Howard</a>, <a href="/wiki/Frank_Owen_(author)" title="Frank Owen (author)">Frank Owen</a>, and <a href="/wiki/E._Hoffmann_Price" title="E. Hoffmann Price">E. Hoffmann Price</a>. In 1932 publication was paused; it was relaunched in 1933 under the title <i>The Magic Carpet Magazine</i>, with an expanded editorial policy that now included any story set in an exotic location, including other planets. Some science fiction began to appear alongside the fantasy and adventure material as a result, including work by <a href="/wiki/Edmond_Hamilton" title="Edmond Hamilton">Edmond Hamilton</a>. Wright obtained stories from <a href="/wiki/Henry_Bedford-Jones" title="Henry Bedford-Jones">H. Bedford Jones</a>, who was a popular pulp writer, and <a href="/wiki/Seabury_Quinn" title="Seabury Quinn">Seabury Quinn</a>. Most of the covers of <i>The Magic Carpet Magazine</i> were by <a href="/wiki/Margaret_Brundage" title="Margaret Brundage">Margaret Brundage</a>. Competition from established pulps in the same niche was too strong, and after five issues under the new title the magazine ceased publication. (<b><a href="/wiki/Oriental_Stories" title="Oriental Stories">Full article...</a></b>)
</p>

<h2 id="mp-dyk-h2" class="mp-h2 mw-html-heading">Did you know ...</h2>
<div id="mp-dyk" class="mp-contains-float">
<div class="dyk-img" style="float: right; margin-left: 0.5em;">
<div class="thumbinner mp-thumb" style="background: transparent; color: inherit; border: none; padding: 0; max-width: 121px;">
<span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Padre_Ottomano1.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="Domenico Ottomano"><img alt="Domenico Ottomano" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Padre_Ottomano1.jpg/250px-Padre_Ottomano1.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="334" class="mw-file-element" data-file-width="960" data-file-height="1284"></a></span><div class="thumbcaption" style="padding: 0.25em 0; word-wrap: break-word;">Domenico Ottomano</div></div>
</div>
<ul><li>... that <b><a href="/wiki/Domenico_Ottomano" title="Domenico Ottomano">the alleged son</a></b> <i>(pictured)</i> of <a href="/wiki/Ibrahim_of_the_Ottoman_Empire" title="Ibrahim of the Ottoman Empire">an Ottoman sultan</a> and <a href="/wiki/Zafire_Hatun" title="Zafire Hatun">an enslaved concubine</a> became a Catholic friar?</li>
<li>... that <b><a href="/wiki/Intersex_healthcare" title="Intersex healthcare">the healthcare needs of intersex people</a></b> depend on what physical characteristics they have?</li>
<li>... that <b><a href="/wiki/Isabella_I_of_Jerusalem" title="Isabella I of Jerusalem">Queen Isabella I</a></b> lost her first husband to politics, her second to assassins, her third to a window, and her fourth to fish?</li>
<li>... that a study in 2024 found that about half of the 500 tonnes (1.1 million lb) of <a href="/wiki/Produce" title="Produce">produce</a> brought to the <b><a href="/wiki/Nueva_Vizcaya_Agricultural_Terminal" title="Nueva Vizcaya Agricultural Terminal">Nueva Vizcaya Agricultural Terminal</a></b> daily was thrown out?</li>
<li>... that <b><a href="/wiki/Thomas_Schubert" title="Thomas Schubert">Thomas Schubert</a></b> made his acting debut on the 2011 film <i><a href="/wiki/Breathing_(film)" title="Breathing (film)">Breathing</a></i>, on the director's insistence that an amateur actor play the leading role?</li>
<li>... that the <b><a href="/wiki/2007_NFC_Championship_Game" title="2007 NFC Championship Game">2007 NFC Championship Game</a></b>, with a temperature of 3 F (19 C) and <a href="/wiki/Wind_chill" title="Wind chill">wind chill</a> as low as 24 F (31 C), was one of the coldest games in <a href="/wiki/Lambeau_Field" title="Lambeau Field">Lambeau Field</a> history?</li>
<li>... that Sir <b><a href="/wiki/Frederic_Willans" title="Frederic Willans">Frederic Willans</a></b> attended the deathbeds of <a href="/wiki/Alexandra_of_Denmark" title="Alexandra of Denmark">Queen Alexandra</a> and her son <a href="/wiki/George_V" title="George V">King George V</a>?</li>
<li>... that while the United States publicly denied any wrongdoing in a <b><a href="/wiki/2013_Radda_airstrike" title="2013 Radda airstrike">2013 drone strike on a wedding convoy</a></b>, it likely gave over $1 million in compensation to the victims' families?</li>
<li>... that <b><a href="/wiki/Alexander_McIver" title="Alexander McIver">Alexander McIver</a></b> took his fight to remain North Carolina's superintendent of public instruction all the way to the state supreme court?</li></ul>

<h2 id="mp-otd-h2" class="mp-h2 mw-html-heading">On this day</h2>
<div id="mp-otd" class="mp-contains-float">
<p><b><a href="/wiki/October_26" title="October 26">October 26</a></b>
</p>
<div style="float:right;margin-left:0.5em;" id="mp-otd-img">
<div class="thumbinner mp-thumb" style="background: transparent; color: inherit; border: none; padding: 0; max-width: 128px;">
<span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Laurent_Gbagbo_(2008).jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="Laurent Gbagbo"><img alt="Laurent Gbagbo" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Laurent_Gbagbo_%282008%29.jpg/250px-Laurent_Gbagbo_%282008%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="299" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Laurent_Gbagbo_%282008%29.jpg/330px-Laurent_Gbagbo_%282008%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="894" data-file-height="1068"></a></span><div class="thumbcaption" style="padding: 0.25em 0; word-wrap: break-word;">Laurent Gbagbo</div></div>
</div>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/1597" title="1597">1597</a>  <a href="/wiki/Imjin_War" title="Imjin War">Imjin War</a>: Thirteen Korean ships commanded by Admiral <a href="/wiki/Yi_Sun-sin" title="Yi Sun-sin">Yi Sun-sin</a> defeated a far larger Japanese invading fleet at the <b><a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Myeongnyang" title="Battle of Myeongnyang">Battle of Myeongnyang</a></b> in the <a href="/wiki/Myeongnyang_Strait" title="Myeongnyang Strait">Myeongnyang Strait</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/1813" title="1813">1813</a>  <a href="/wiki/War_of_1812" title="War of 1812">War of 1812</a>: British forces and <a href="/wiki/Mohawk_people" title="Mohawk people">Mohawk</a> allies under <a href="/wiki/Charles_de_Salaberry" title="Charles de Salaberry">Charles de Salaberry</a> <b><a href="/wiki/Battle_of_the_Chateauguay" title="Battle of the Chateauguay">repulsed an American attempt to invade Canada</a></b>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/1902" title="1902">1902</a>  A group of Russian explorers led by <a href="/wiki/Eduard_von_Toll" title="Eduard von Toll">Baron von Toll</a> left their camp on <a href="/wiki/Bennett_Island" title="Bennett Island">Bennett Island</a> and <b><a href="/wiki/Russian_polar_expedition_of_1900%E2%80%931902" title="Russian polar expedition of 19001902">disappeared without a trace</a></b>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/1905" title="1905">1905</a>  The <b><a href="/wiki/Saint_Petersburg_Soviet" title="Saint Petersburg Soviet">Saint Petersburg Soviet</a></b> held its first meeting, becoming the first <a href="/wiki/Soviet_(council)" title="Soviet (council)">elected body in Russia to represent workers</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/2000" title="2000">2000</a>  Following protests against military leader <a href="/wiki/Robert_Gu%C3%A9%C3%AF" title="Robert Gu">Robert Gu</a>, <b><a href="/wiki/Laurent_Gbagbo" title="Laurent Gbagbo">Laurent Gbagbo</a></b> <i>(pictured)</i> became the <a href="/wiki/List_of_heads_of_state_of_Ivory_Coast" title="List of heads of state of Ivory Coast">president of Ivory Coast</a>.</li></ul>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1129693374"><div class="hlist" style="margin-top: 0.5em;"><ul><li><b><a href="/wiki/Sir_John_Gell,_1st_Baronet" title="Sir John Gell, 1st Baronet">Sir John Gell, 1st Baronet</a></b>  (<abbr title="died">d.</abbr> 1671)</li><li><b><a href="/wiki/C._W._Post" title="C. <h2 id="mp-tfp-h2" class="mp-h2 mw-html-heading">Today's featured picture</h2>
<div id="mp-tfp">
<table role="presentation" style="margin:0 3px 3px; width:100%; box-sizing:border-box; text-align:left; border-collapse:collapse;">
<tbody><tr>
<td style="padding:0 0.9em 0 0; width:400px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="Grey-breasted partridge"><img alt="Grey-breasted partridge" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg/500px-Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg" decoding="async" width="500" height="333" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg/960px-Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg 1.5x" data-file-width="4409" data-file-height="2939"></a></span>
</td>
<td style="padding:0 6px 0 0">
<p>The <b><a href="/wiki/Grey-breasted_partridge" title="Grey-breasted partridge">grey-breasted partridge</a></b> (<i>Arborophila orientalis</i>) is a bird species in the family <a href="/wiki/Phasianidae" title="Phasianidae">Phasianidae</a>. It is endemic to <a href="/wiki/Montane_ecosystem#Montane_forests" title="Montane ecosystem">highland forest</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Eastern_salient_of_Java" title="Eastern salient of Java">eastern salient of Java</a>, Indonesia. Measuring 28 cm (11 in), the species is a stocky, short-legged bird. Its mostly grey plumage is barred on the lower back and tail. It has a black crown and nape, and conspicuous white forehead, cheeks and throat. The bare skin around the eyes is red, as are the legs, while the bill is black. This grey-breasted partridge was photographed in a nature preserve near the volcanic crater of <a href="/wiki/Ijen" title="Ijen">Ijen</a> in <a href="/wiki/Banyuwangi_Regency" title="Banyuwangi Regency">Banyuwangi Regency</a>, Java.
</p>
<p style="text-align:left;"><small>Photograph credit: <a href="/wiki/User:JJ_Harrison" title="User:JJ Harrison">JJ Harrison</a></small></p>

    From today's featured article

    Cover of first issue (October/November1930)

    Oriental Stories was an American pulp magazine published by Popular Fiction and edited by Farnsworth Wright. It was launched in 1930 as a companion to Popular Fiction's Weird Tales, and carried stories with Far Eastern settings, including some fantasy. Contributors included Robert E. Howard, Frank Owen, and E.Hoffmann Price. In 1932 publication was paused; it was relaunched in 1933 under the title The Magic Carpet Magazine, with an expanded editorial policy that now included any story set in an exotic location, including other planets. Some science fiction began to appear alongside the fantasy and adventure material as a result, including work by Edmond Hamilton. Wright obtained stories from H.Bedford Jones, who was a popular pulp writer, and Seabury Quinn. Most of the covers of The Magic Carpet Magazine were by Margaret Brundage. Competition from established pulps in the same niche was too strong, and after five issues under the new title the magazine ceased publication. (Fullarticle...)

    Did you know...

    Domenico Ottomano

From today's featured article

Cover of first issue (October/November1930)

Oriental Stories was an American pulp magazine published by Popular Fiction and edited by Farnsworth Wright. It was launched in 1930 as a companion to Popular Fiction's Weird Tales, and carried stories with Far Eastern settings, including some fantasy. Contributors included Robert E. Howard, Frank Owen, and E.Hoffmann Price. In 1932 publication was paused; it was relaunched in 1933 under the title The Magic Carpet Magazine, with an expanded editorial policy that now included any story set in an exotic location, including other planets. Some science fiction began to appear alongside the fantasy and adventure material as a result, including work by Edmond Hamilton. Wright obtained stories from H.Bedford Jones, who was a popular pulp writer, and Seabury Quinn. Most of the covers of The Magic Carpet Magazine were by Margaret Brundage. Competition from established pulps in the same niche was too strong, and after five issues under the new title the magazine ceased publication. (Fullarticle...)

The grey-breasted partridge (Arborophila orientalis) is a bird species in the family Phasianidae. It is endemic to highland forest in the eastern salient of Java, Indonesia. Measuring 28cm (11in), the species is a stocky, short-legged bird. Its mostly grey plumage is barred on the lower back and tail. It has a black crown and nape, and conspicuous white forehead, cheeks and throat. The bare skin around the eyes is red, as are the legs, while the bill is black. This grey-breasted partridge was photographed in a nature preserve near the volcanic crater of Ijen in Banyuwangi Regency, Java.

Photograph credit: JJ Harrison

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
# Welcome to [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia "Wikipedia")
,
the [free](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_content "Free content") [encyclopedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encyclopedia "Encyclopedia") that [anyone can edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_Wikipedia "Help:Introduction to Wikipedia").
  * [114,046](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:Statistics "Special:Statistics") active editors
  * [7,080,403](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:Statistics "Special:Statistics") articles in [English](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_language "English language")


## From today's featured article
[![Cover of first issue \(October/November1930\)](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg/120px-Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg "Cover of first issue \(October/November1930\)")
Cover of first issue (October/November 1930)
_**[Oriental Stories](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oriental_Stories "Oriental Stories")**_ was an American [pulp magazine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulp_magazine "Pulp magazine") published by Popular Fiction and edited by [Farnsworth Wright](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Farnsworth_Wright "Farnsworth Wright"). It was launched in 1930 as a companion to Popular Fiction's _[Weird Tales](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weird_Tales "Weird Tales")_ , and carried [stories with Far Eastern settings](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orientalism "Orientalism"), including some fantasy. Contributors included [Robert E. Howard](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_E._Howard "Robert E. Howard"), [Frank Owen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Owen_\(author\) "Frank Owen \(author\)"), and [E. Hoffmann Price](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E._Hoffmann_Price "E. Hoffmann Price"). In 1932 publication was paused; it was relaunched in 1933 under the title _The Magic Carpet Magazine_ , with an expanded editorial policy that now included any story set in an exotic location, including other planets. Some science fiction began to appear alongside the fantasy and adventure material as a result, including work by [Edmond Hamilton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edmond_Hamilton "Edmond Hamilton"). Wright obtained stories from [H. Bedford Jones](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Bedford-Jones "Henry Bedford-Jones"), who was a popular pulp writer, and [Seabury Quinn](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seabury_Quinn "Seabury Quinn"). Most of the covers of _The Magic Carpet Magazine_ were by [Margaret Brundage](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Brundage "Margaret Brundage"). Competition from established pulps in the same niche was too strong, and after five issues under the new title the magazine ceased publication. (**[Full article...](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oriental_Stories "Oriental Stories")**)

## Did you know ...
[![Domenico Ottomano](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Padre_Ottomano1.jpg/250px-Padre_Ottomano1.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Padre_Ottomano1.jpg "Domenico Ottomano")
Domenico Ottomano
  * ... that **[the alleged son](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domenico_Ottomano "Domenico Ottomano")** _(pictured)_ of [an Ottoman sultan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibrahim_of_the_Ottoman_Empire "Ibrahim of the Ottoman Empire") and [an enslaved concubine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zafire_Hatun "Zafire Hatun") became a Catholic friar?
  * ... that **[the healthcare needs of intersex people](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intersex_healthcare "Intersex healthcare")** depend on what physical characteristics they have?
  * ... that **[Queen Isabella I](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isabella_I_of_Jerusalem "Isabella I of Jerusalem")** lost her first husband to politics, her second to assassins, her third to a window, and her fourth to fish?
  * ... that a study in 2024 found that about half of the 500 tonnes (1.1 million lb) of [produce](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Produce "Produce") brought to the **[Nueva Vizcaya Agricultural Terminal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nueva_Vizcaya_Agricultural_Terminal "Nueva Vizcaya Agricultural Terminal")** daily was thrown out?
  * ... that **[Thomas Schubert](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Schubert "Thomas Schubert")** made his acting debut on the 2011 film _[Breathing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breathing_\(film\) "Breathing \(film\)")_ , on the director's insistence that an amateur actor play the leading role?
  * ... that the **[2007 NFC Championship Game](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_NFC_Championship_Game "2007 NFC Championship Game")** , with a temperature of 3 F (19 C) and [wind chill](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wind_chill "Wind chill") as low as 24 F (31 C), was one of the coldest games in [Lambeau Field](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lambeau_Field "Lambeau Field") history?
  * ... that Sir **[Frederic Willans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederic_Willans "Frederic Willans")** attended the deathbeds of [Queen Alexandra](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandra_of_Denmark "Alexandra of Denmark") and her son [King George V](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_V "George V")?
  * ... that while the United States publicly denied any wrongdoing in a **[2013 drone strike on a wedding convoy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_Radda_airstrike "2013 Radda airstrike")** , it likely gave over $1 million in compensation to the victims' families?
  * ... that **[Alexander McIver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_McIver "Alexander McIver")** took his fight to remain North Carolina's superintendent of public instruction all the way to the state supreme court?

## On this day
**[October 26](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/October_26 "October 26")**
[![Laurent Gbagbo](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Laurent_Gbagbo_%282008%29.jpg/250px-Laurent_Gbagbo_%282008%29.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Laurent_Gbagbo_\(2008\).jpg "Laurent Gbagbo")
Laurent Gbagbo
  * [1597](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1597 "1597")  [Imjin War](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imjin_War "Imjin War"): Thirteen Korean ships commanded by Admiral [Yi Sun-sin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yi_Sun-sin "Yi Sun-sin") defeated a far larger Japanese invading fleet at the **[Battle of Myeongnyang](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Myeongnyang "Battle of Myeongnyang")** in the [Myeongnyang Strait](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myeongnyang_Strait "Myeongnyang Strait").
  * [1813](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1813 "1813")  [War of 1812](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_of_1812 "War of 1812"): British forces and [Mohawk](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohawk_people "Mohawk people") allies under [Charles de Salaberry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_de_Salaberry "Charles de Salaberry") **[repulsed an American attempt to invade Canada](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Chateauguay "Battle of the Chateauguay")**.
  * [1902](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1902 "1902")  A group of Russian explorers led by [Baron von Toll](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eduard_von_Toll "Eduard von Toll") left their camp on [Bennett Island](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bennett_Island "Bennett Island") and **[disappeared without a trace](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_polar_expedition_of_1900%E2%80%931902 "Russian polar expedition of 19001902")**.
  * [1905](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1905 "1905")  The **[Saint Petersburg Soviet](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Petersburg_Soviet "Saint Petersburg Soviet")** held its first meeting, becoming the first [elected body in Russia to represent workers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soviet_\(council\) "Soviet \(council\)").
  * [2000](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2000 "2000")  Following protests against military leader [Robert Gu](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Gu%C3%A9%C3%AF "Robert Gu"), **[Laurent Gbagbo](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurent_Gbagbo "Laurent Gbagbo")** _(pictured)_ became the [president of Ivory Coast](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_heads_of_state_of_Ivory_Coast "List of heads of state of Ivory Coast").


  * **[Sir John Gell, 1st Baronet](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_John_Gell,_1st_Baronet "Sir John Gell, 1st Baronet")** (d. 1671)

## Today's featured picture
[![Grey-breasted partridge](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg/500px-Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg "Grey-breasted partridge") |  The **[grey-breasted partridge](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey-breasted_partridge "Grey-breasted partridge")** (_Arborophila orientalis_) is a bird species in the family [Phasianidae](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phasianidae "Phasianidae"). It is endemic to [highland forest](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montane_ecosystem#Montane_forests "Montane ecosystem") in the [eastern salient of Java](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_salient_of_Java "Eastern salient of Java"), Indonesia. Measuring 28 cm (11 in), the species is a stocky, short-legged bird. Its mostly grey plumage is barred on the lower back and tail. It has a black crown and nape, and conspicuous white forehead, cheeks and throat. The bare skin around the eyes is red, as are the legs, while the bill is black. This grey-breasted partridge was photographed in a nature preserve near the volcanic crater of [Ijen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ijen "Ijen") in [Banyuwangi Regency](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banyuwangi_Regency "Banyuwangi Regency"), Java.  Photograph credit: [JJ Harrison](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User:JJ_Harrison "User:JJ Harrison") Recently featured:

## From today's featured article
![Cover of first issue \(October/November1930\)59](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Oriental_Stories_October-November_1930.jpg "Cover of first issue \(October/November1930\)")
Cover of first issue (October/November 1930)
_**Oriental Stories60**_ was an American pulp magazine61 published by Popular Fiction and edited by Farnsworth Wright62. It was launched in 1930 as a companion to Popular Fiction's _Weird Tales63_ , and carried stories with Far Eastern settings64, including some fantasy. Contributors included Robert E. Howard65, Frank Owen66 "Frank Owen \(author\)"), and E. Hoffmann Price67. In 1932 publication was paused; it was relaunched in 1933 under the title _The Magic Carpet Magazine_ , with an expanded editorial policy that now included any story set in an exotic location, including other planets. Some science fiction began to appear alongside the fantasy and adventure material as a result, including work by Edmond Hamilton68. Wright obtained stories from H. Bedford Jones69, who was a popular pulp writer, and Seabury Quinn70. Most of the covers of _The Magic Carpet Magazine_ were by Margaret Brundage71. Competition from established pulps in the same niche was too strong, and after five issues under the new title the magazine ceased publication. (**Full article...60**)

## Today's featured picture
![Grey-breasted partridge162](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gray-breasted_Partridge_0A2A3088.jpg "Grey-breasted partridge") |  The **grey-breasted partridge163** (_Arborophila orientalis_) is a bird species in the family Phasianidae164. It is endemic to highland forest165 in the eastern salient of Java166, Indonesia. Measuring 28 cm (11 in), the species is a stocky, short-legged bird. Its mostly grey plumage is barred on the lower back and tail. It has a black crown and nape, and conspicuous white forehead, cheeks and throat. The bare skin around the eyes is red, as are the legs, while the bill is black. This grey-breasted partridge was photographed in a nature preserve near the volcanic crater of Ijen167 in Banyuwangi Regency168, Java.  Photograph credit: JJ Harrison169 Recently featured:
